Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

This is not fixed and I'm seeing it with a recent version of stable/kilo.

All VM snapshot images created by libvirt KVM driver in Nova that did not have ramdisk or kernel_id values will exhibit this behavior and they will fail to boot/spawn/deploy when Nova moves to use Glance v2.

VM snapshot images using the rbd ephemeral snapshot code, https://review.openstack.org/#/c/125963/, are already exhibiting the failure behavior for me because this spawn path uses a Glance v2 call to get image locations.

Patch Set 3:

@Mike

http://paste.openstack.org/show/380777 shows a definite bug -- along the lines of what is fixed in https://review.openstack.org/#/c/199104.

But I don't think it reproduces this bug.

Your v1 client command has created new *user defined properties* which happen to be called 'ramdisk_id' and 'kernel_id'. You have not written 'null' to the built-in 'ramdisk_id' or 'kernel_id'. The client then gets confused applying the schema for the built-in properties to those user defined properties. That is a separate bug. If you could enter a ticket for it that would be super! Thanks.

I'll try to take another look at this bug based on the additional info in the bug report.

Patch Set 3:

@Mike

Apologies, a long time ago the command to add ramdisk/kernel was --ramdisk-id/--kernel-id. Now it is just to use the standard --property as you did. You did add regular properties -- but that's the correct command.

Similarly, it's possible to successfully add a kernel_id which is just an integer ("1234") using v1, and which will then fail the schema check with v2:

$ glance --os-image-api-version 2 image-show 77eb9a7a-e781-46b0-9b6f-292c02f28af4
u'1234' does not match u'^([0-9a-fA-F]){8}-([0-9a-fA-F]){4}-([0-9a-fA-F]){4}-([0-9a-fA-F]){4}-([0-9a-fA-F]){12}$'

Failed validating u'pattern' in schema[u'properties'][u'kernel_id']:
    {u'description': u'ID of image stored in Glance that should be used as the kernel when booting an AMI-style image.',
     u'is_base': False,
     u'pattern': u'^([0-9a-fA-F]){8}-([0-9a-fA-F]){4}-([0-9a-fA-F]){4}-([0-9a-fA-F]){4}-([0-9a-fA-F]){12}$',
     u'type': u'string'}

On instance[u'kernel_id']:
    u'1234'

So it looks like we have a general mis-match between what v1 allows you to store and what v2 expects.

Patch Set 3: -Code-Review

Removing -2.

This is an API change and, from memory, we hit issues when we did a similar thing with disk-format/container-format, so we need to really think this through.

Patch Set 3: Code-Review+2

I don't think this is a big API change. TBH, the real fix is to simply have Nova not adding null ramdisk_id/kernel_id. However, I'm happy about having this since, to the best of my knowledge, it doesn't seem disruptive.

Stuart, I'll let you approve if you agree

Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

Short version -- this looks good to me, thanks.

We should add APIImpact to the commit message as per https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GitCommitMessages. (-1 for this ... just paperwork, I can add it myself tomorrow if nobody gets a chance to do it.)

Louis reminded me what the issue was when we made an equivalent change with disk-format/container-format: older clients were broken because they were not able to handle the null parameter when it was returned by the server.

I went back to glance client 0.12.0 (the version that comes with Debian 8) and checked that the image-show and image-list commands still worked ok for both v1 and v2 with this change on the server side. This change fixes the issue for the 0.12.0 client also.

Thanks to Mike for finally figuring out how to reproduce with 'image-list' as opposed to image-show (delete all images except for one). Lack of being able to reproduce held this review up -- apologies to the submitters. We can think about potentially changing the list behaviour w.r.t schema validation. (For performance we currently check only the first image of each batch that the server returns, but this can lead to unpredictable behaviour.)
